Table S2 showed the longitudinal association between sleep duration, sarcopenia, and successful aging by GLMM. After adjusting for potential confounders, compared with sleep duration of less than 6 h, sleep durations of 6–8, 8–9, and ≥ 9 h were associated with 102% (OR = 2.02, 96% CI: 1.74–2.35), 116% (OR = 2.16, 96% CI: 1.82–2.56), and 47% (OR = 1.47, 96% CI: 1.24–1.74) higher odds of achieving successful aging, respectively. In contrast, compared to older adults without sarcopenia, those with possible sarcopenia and sarcopenia had significantly lower odds of achieving successful aging. The likelihood ratio test comparing the mixed-effects model with a standard logistic regression model indicated a significantly better fit for the mixed model (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
